File: e2e/browser-tools.e2e.ts

WebSocket frame clear race (lines 2020-2024): After calling browser_get_websocket_frames with clear: true, the test immediately calls it again and asserts frames.length === 0. The /ws-test page has an active WebSocket that could receive new frames between the two calls. Compare with the HTTP network capture clear tests (around lines 1716 and 1903) which use waitFor to drain the buffer. Apply the same pattern: poll until the frame buffer stays empty for 2-3 consecutive checks.

Dialog unbounded promise (lines 2579-2588): The dialogHandled promise uses page.on('dialog', ...) with no timeout. If the alert never fires, the test hangs for the full test timeout. Add a setTimeout wrapper:

const dialogHandled = Promise.race([
  new Promise<void>(resolve => {
    tabPage.once('dialog', async dialog => {
      // handle dialog
      resolve();
    });
  }),
  new Promise<void>((_, reject) =>
    setTimeout(() => reject(new Error('Dialog not received within 10s')), 10_000)
  ),
]);

Use tabPage.once() instead of tabPage.on() to auto-remove the listener.

Files: e2e/structured-errors.e2e.ts, e2e/sdk-fetch-errors.e2e.ts, e2e/sdk-utilities.e2e.ts

All three files follow the same pattern: each test calls setupToolTest() or setupSdkTest() which returns a page, runs assertions, then calls page.close() at the end. If an assertion fails mid-test, page.close() is never reached.

Fix: wrap each test body in try/finally:

test('test name', async ({ ... }) => {
  const page = await setupToolTest(...);
  try {
    // existing test body
  } finally {
    await page.close();
  }
});

This is a mechanical transformation. Apply it to every test in all three files. The page.close() call at the end of the try block can be removed since finally handles it.
